                  "body": {
                    "type": "TextualBody",
                    "value": "<p rend=\"align(right)\">\n                <placeName>Richmond</placeName>\n                <date>June 14.1849</date>\n            </p>\n            <p>Valued Friend</p>\n            <p rend=\"indent(1)\">I perceived in the last no of<lb/> the “Occident” an article written by<lb/>\n                <persName>Mr Brown</persName> relative to the <date>Sunday</date><lb/> Laws of\n                    <placeName>Pennsylvania</placeName>, and I regret<lb/> much that every effort\n                has been in<lb/> vain to modify that obnoxious Law<lb/> in your state, a session\n                before the<lb/> last of our Legislature when they revis-<lb/>ed our Criminal Laws I\n                had the<lb/> matter under consideration in the<lb/> Senate nearly two days relative\n                to<lb/> the <date>Sabbath</date> Laws here in which<lb/>\n                <persName>Mr <sic>Stanard</sic></persName> and others took a very<lb/> active part.\n                I think that I sent you<lb/> the papers containing the remarks<lb/> on the subject,\n                they were however only<lb/> slightly modified and that only by<lb/> the casting vote\n                of the speaker, the law<lb/> as reported by the revisers read thus<lb/> “If any\n                person on <date>Sabbath</date> day shall<lb/> himself be found labouring &amp;c\n                &amp;c” and<lb/> the amendment asked for in the Senate<lb/> was a proviso for\n                persons who had<lb/> kept the <date>Sabbath</date> day of the congregation<lb/> to\n                which they may have belonged to be<lb/> exempt from the penalty of the law</p>"
                  },
                  "target": "https://colenda.library.upenn.edu/items/ark:/81431/p3cc0vd5b/canvas/p1"
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
