                  "type": "Annotation",
                  "motivation": "commenting",
                  "body": {
                    "type": "TextualBody",
                    "value": "<p>which was lost by a vote of 20 to 5<lb/> the amendment was then asked for to<lb/>\n                insert the word “a” so as to read “If any<lb/> person on <hi rend=\"underline\">a</hi>\n                <date>sabbath</date> day “&amp;c &amp;c” and in order<lb/> to get that slight\n                amendment it was<lb/> a tie vote the speaker giving the casting<lb/> vote. You will\n                perceive that the<lb/> law as reported was done to recognize<lb/> a\n                    <date>Sabbath</date> day and not to leave it dis-<lb/>cretionary with the\n                magistrate to say<lb/> which was the <date>sabbath</date> day, the title<lb/> of the\n                Chapter in which this law may<lb/> be found in Chap VIII “Of\n                <sic>offences</sic><lb/> against Chastity Morality and Decency”<lb/> Revised Code\n                    <date>1848</date> page III. <persName>Mr Mays</persName><lb/> and\n                    <persName>Standard</persName> told me then that if<lb/> we had have had any\n                    '<sic>competant</sic><lb/> person to have argued the point before<lb/> the\n                committee we would have had<lb/> matters fixed our own way, but in<lb/> this\n                particular we were minus.</p>\n            <p rend=\"indent(1)\">We have now an extra session<lb/> of the Legislature for the purpose\n                of<lb/> revising the Civil Code and I believe<lb/> the Criminal also. I regret that\n                they<lb/> have adjourned from here to the<lb/> springs. I did intend to use my\n                eff<lb/>orts to get this matter set right in</p>"
                  },
                  "target": "https://colenda.library.upenn.edu/items/ark:/81431/p3cc0vd5b/canvas/p2"
                }
              ]
            }
